<p>
St. Brendan's parish is fortunate in that it possesses a chalice from the penal era, which the Dominican Father Thomas Cummins had made for his friary in Athy in 1734. The Franciscans at Multyfarnham Abbey, County Westmeath, preserve a second penal chalice with a connection to St. Brendan's. Made in 1717, the inscription prays for the soul of Patrick Tuite and requests that it be given to Multyfarnham. A Franciscan had possibly ministered in Coolock, or perhaps it belonged to Canon Andrew Tuite, parish priest of Coolock from 1733 to 1771. Either way, both chalices are a precious and tangible reminder of that era of persecution.<br /><br />

By the end of the eighteenth century, the injustice of the penal laws had begun to warrant the attention of many of the patriots in the parliament at College Green. By 1782 most of the penal laws that limited religious practice were removed, but the big political obstacles remained. Amongst the most vocal in support of Catholic emancipation was Henry Grattan, born at Belcamp Park, who famously declared that 'so long as the Penal code remains we shall never be a great nation'. In the 1790s, the United Irishmen, whose aim was to unite 'protestant, catholic and dissenter under the common name for Irishman', took up the cause. They aimed to establish an Irish republic free from sectarian divisions, but their connections with revolutionary France alarmed Dublin Castle and resulted in tough law and order policies which inflicted terror on the land. As Ireland drifted towards war, the people armed themselves for both their defence and the planned rebellion of 1798.<br /><br />
</p>
